<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-453685">
<article id="comment-453685" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<cite><b class="fn">nick</b> </cite><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230122074248/https://www.nakedcapitalism.com/2011/08/what-is-debt-%e2%80%93-an-interview-with-economic-anthropologist-david-graeber.html#comment-453685"><time datetime="2011-08-27T23:00:04-04:00">August 27, 2011 at 11:00 pm</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>Thats a pretty insightful explanation, however the time money thing is debatable. Because although a doctors appointment can be completed in half an hour, it took that doctor many years to acquire the skills and education necessary to be a doctor. So what do you time trade to equal twelve years of education? In Thomas Sowell&#8217;s Basic Economics, he states a scenario where a painter on the side of the street paints a man in five minutes. The man says &#8220;wow, that is amazing, how much do i owe you?&#8221; the painter says &#8220;one hundred dollars&#8221;. the man says, &#8220;well thats a little overpriced seeing as how it only took you five minutes, but its very good, so ill pay you&#8221; the painter says &#8220;yes, twenty years ,and five minutes&#8221;.</p>
</section>
<div class="reply">
